{"id":"1512.09084","submitter":"Ariel Caticha","authors":"Daniel Bartolomeo and Ariel Caticha","title":"Entropic Dynamics: The Schroedinger equation and its Bohmian limit","comments":"Presented at MaxEnt 2015, the 35th International Workshop on Bayesian\n  Inference and Maximum Entropy Methods in Science and Engineering (July\n  19--24, 2015, Potsdam NY, USA). arXiv admin note: text overlap with\n  arXiv:1603.08469","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In the Entropic Dynamics (ED) derivation of the Schroedinger equation the\nphysical input is introduced through constraints that are implemented using\nLagrange multipliers. There is one constraint involving a \"drift\" potential\nthat correlates the motions of different particles and is ultimately\nresponsible for entanglement. The purpose of this work is to deepen our\nunderstanding of the corresponding multiplier. Its main effect is to control\nthe strength of the drift relative to the fluctuations. We show that ED\nexhibits a symmetry: models with different values of the multiplier can lead to\nthe same Schroedinger equation; different \"microscopic\" or sub-quantum models\nlead to the same \"macroscopic\" or quantum behavior. As the multiplier tends to\ninfinity the drift prevails over the fluctuations and the particles tend to\nmove along the smooth probability flow lines. Thus ED includes the causal or\nBohmian form of quantum mechanics as a special limiting case.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Dec 2015 19:54:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 22 Jun 2017 18:04:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-06-27"}
